00:39:06,878 --> 00:39:10,257
that you would really
let yourself say,

743
00:39:10,281 --> 00:39:11,358
"This is it."

744
00:39:11,382 --> 00:39:14,328
Its real significance
is that it's the first place

745
00:39:14,352 --> 00:39:16,530
in the United States

746
00:39:16,554 --> 00:39:19,266
that Europeans came and stayed.

747
00:39:19,290 --> 00:39:22,269
- And there's evidence of the
children who first came here,

748
00:39:22,293 --> 00:39:23,470
as well.

749
00:39:23,494 --> 00:39:27,007
- We found a little figa amulet,

750
00:39:27,031 --> 00:39:29,343
which is a little clenched fist

751
00:39:29,367 --> 00:39:31,478
with the thumb
between the fingers,

752
00:39:31,502 --> 00:39:35,749
and Spanish women
had many of these

753
00:39:35,773 --> 00:39:37,885
hanging around babies necks

754
00:39:37,909 --> 00:39:40,688
to protect them
against evil eye,

755
00:39:40,712 --> 00:39:43,490
and we just couldn't
help imagining

756
00:39:43,514 --> 00:39:46,760
that this was associated
with the first European child

757
00:39:46,784 --> 00:39:49,430
born in what's now
the United States,

758
00:39:49,454 --> 00:39:51,632
Martinico de Arguelles.

759
00:39:51,656 --> 00:39:54,768
- And we have references
to children being born

760
00:39:54,792 --> 00:39:57,905
in Saint Augustine obviously
soon after people arrive.

761
00:39:57,929 --> 00:40:01,041
- Dr. Susan Parker scours
parish records

762
00:40:01,065 --> 00:40:03,444
now housed in Saint Augustine

763
00:40:03,468 --> 00:40:06,680
to reconstruct the lives
of ordinary people.

764
00:40:06,704 --> 00:40:10,517
- It's just whatever you can find
to try to piece them together

765
00:40:10,541 --> 00:40:14,788
and give a voice
and a face to many people

766
00:40:14,812 --> 00:40:18,525
that wouldn't have a voice
and a face otherwise.

767
00:40:18,549 --> 00:40:22,596
- Women and children are often
missing from official accounts,

768
00:40:22,620 --> 00:40:24,932
but Parker has managed
to breathe life in

769
00:40:24,956 --> 00:40:27,601
to these first families
through their letters

770
00:40:27,625 --> 00:40:31,338
back to Spain and vital records.

771
00:40:31,362 --> 00:40:33,841
- I think we need to remember
that it's 42 years

772
00:40:33,865 --> 00:40:36,443
between when Saint Augustine
was founded

773
00:40:36,467 --> 00:40:39,446
and when Jamestown is founded.

774
00:40:39,470 --> 00:40:41,415
If we look at that
in a different way,

775
00:40:41,439 --> 00:40:43,817
that's almost two generations.

776
00:40:43,841 --> 00:40:46,420
In other words, the children
who stepped to shore,

777
00:40:46,444 --> 00:40:48,722
however many children there
were, with Pedro Menéndez

778
00:40:48,746 --> 00:40:51,358
probably had their own
grandchildren by the time

779
00:40:51,382 --> 00:40:53,894
Jamestown was founded.

780
00:40:53,918 --> 00:40:57,364
- Another discovery, the
important role native women

781
00:40:57,388 --> 00:41:00,567
played in providing food
for the new colony.

782
00:41:00,591 --> 00:41:03,037
- We have found
the remains of foods

783
00:41:03,061 --> 00:41:06,373
that they must have
learned about the foods

784
00:41:06,397 --> 00:41:10,878
and how to fix them from
the native people in the area,

785
00:41:10,902 --> 00:41:15,115
and this, I think,
is a real indication

786
00:41:15,139 --> 00:41:16,984
that Native American women,

787
00:41:17,008 --> 00:41:22,389
even though they were invisible
in much of the document record,

788
00:41:22,413 --> 00:41:25,025
really shaped the actual
life experiences

789
00:41:25,049 --> 00:41:27,895
of everyone in these colonies.

790
00:41:27,919 --> 00:41:30,798
- At first, the relationship
between the natives

791
00:41:30,822 --> 00:41:33,534
and Spanish settlers
was a good one.

792
00:41:33,558 --> 00:41:36,637
It's said the Timucuan
Indian chief named Soloy

793
00:41:36,661 --> 00:41:39,873
gave Pedro Menéndez
his own council house,

794
00:41:39,897 --> 00:41:43,610
big enough to hold
hundreds of people.

795
00:41:43,634 --> 00:41:46,013
- In this GIS map
just happens to show

796
00:41:46,037 --> 00:41:49,149
where all the post molds
and big pits are.

797
00:41:49,173 --> 00:41:51,485
- It's believed that an
archaeologist may have

798
00:41:51,509 --> 00:41:54,822
discovered
this round house in the 1950s,

799
00:41:54,846 --> 00:41:57,891
but his findings
were never published.

800
00:41:57,915 --> 00:42:00,661
All of those records recently
turned up in a garage

801
00:42:00,685 --> 00:42:04,765
in California
nearly 70 years later.

802
00:42:04,789 --> 00:42:08,035
Deagan and her team plan
to search for that round house,

803
00:42:08,059 --> 00:42:11,638
but in the meantime,
they've made another discovery.

804
00:42:11,662 --> 00:42:14,775
Deagan believes they may
have found the walls

805
00:42:14,799 --> 00:42:18,112
of this settlement's first fort.

806
00:42:18,136 --> 00:42:22,516
- In 1565, the ground surface
would have been somewhere

807
00:42:22,540 --> 00:42:25,452
in this area,

808
00:42:25,476 --> 00:42:27,054
and this is where, for example,

809
00:42:27,078 --> 00:42:32,126
if somebody was standing
and dug this hole for a wall,

810
00:42:32,150 --> 00:42:34,795
their feet would have been.

811
00:42:34,819 --> 00:42:38,532
- Menéndez ordered a fort
to be built just before he left

812
00:42:38,556 --> 00:42:40,534
to start up other
fortified settlements

813
00:42:40,558 --> 00:42:44,538
along the east coast.

814
00:42:44,562 --> 00:42:46,840
He was gone
more than four months,

815
00:42:46,864 --> 00:42:49,834
but by winter, rations and
supplies were becoming scarce.

816
00:42:52,904 --> 00:42:57,584
- They complained of starvation
and Indian attacks,

817
00:42:57,608 --> 00:42:59,953
and most of the people
who came here with Menéndez

818
00:42:59,977 --> 00:43:03,023
came because they assumed
they would have a better life.

819
00:43:03,047 --> 00:43:04,224
They would have livestock.

820
00:43:04,248 --> 00:43:06,026
They might find gold and riches.

821
00:43:06,050 --> 00:43:07,861
They would have
their own piece of land,

822
00:43:07,885 --> 00:43:10,864
but none of that ever happened.

823
00:43:10,888 --> 00:43:12,866
- A group of discontented
soldiers

824
00:43:12,890 --> 00:43:15,602
began plotting a mutiny.

825
00:43:15,626 --> 00:43:18,005
- So within six months
of arriving,

826
00:43:18,029 --> 00:43:22,176
most of the soldiers decided
that they had enough,

827
00:43:22,200 --> 00:43:24,611
and said "We're just going
to capture a boat.

828
00:43:24,635 --> 00:43:28,015
We're going to get the supplies.
We're going to get out of here."

829
00:43:28,039 --> 00:43:31,785
- At midnight, rebels marched
with torches and guns,

830
00:43:31,809 --> 00:43:33,620
looting Saint Augustine's
store room

831
00:43:33,644 --> 00:43:37,758
and loading weapons on board
a ship headed for Spain.

832
00:43:37,782 --> 00:43:42,296
- They tied up the quartermaster
and took off with the weaponry

833
00:43:42,320 --> 00:43:44,631
and some of the supplies
on a ship,

834
00:43:44,655 --> 00:43:49,036
but the quartermaster was able
to get himself free

835
00:43:49,060 --> 00:43:51,171
with the help of a few
other loyal soldiers,

836
00:43:51,195 --> 00:43:54,808
and he shot at the mutineers.

837
00:43:54,832 --> 00:43:58,045
He did quell the mutiny.

838
00:43:58,069 --> 00:44:02,234
- The leader of the uprising was
immediately hanged for treason.

839
00:44:06,077 --> 00:44:08,922
Pedro Menéndez returned
two weeks later with food

840
00:44:08,946 --> 00:44:10,791
and additional troops.

841
00:44:10,815 --> 00:44:15,062
He pardoned those willing
to swear allegiance to him.

842
00:44:15,086 --> 00:44:18,799
Those who didn't could take
their chances on their own

843
00:44:18,823 --> 00:44:21,335
without a ship or provisions.

844
00:44:21,359 --> 00:44:23,070
- He gave them a choice.

845
00:44:23,094 --> 00:44:29,076
They chose, for the most part,
to go back to Menéndez.

846
00:44:29,100 --> 00:44:32,079
- But it wasn't just the soldiers
who were unhappy.

847
00:44:32,103 --> 00:44:36,817
Evidence of burnt structures
confirms another dark truth...

848
00:44:36,841 --> 00:44:41,588
That the goodwill with the
natives lasted less than a year.

849
00:44:41,612 --> 00:44:44,725
- The Timucua, after nine months,

850
00:44:44,749 --> 00:44:46,693
attacked and burnt part
of the settlement,

851
00:44:46,717 --> 00:44:48,829
and that's when
it was abandoned.

852
00:44:48,853 --> 00:44:52,232
- The settlers had overstayed
their welcome.

853
00:44:52,256 --> 00:44:57,971
♪♪

854
00:44:57,995 --> 00:45:00,841
The settlers moved across
the river to a small piece

855
00:45:00,865 --> 00:45:05,612
of land now known
as Anastasia Island.

856
00:45:05,636 --> 00:45:07,881
The structure that used
to be Fort Caroline

857
00:45:07,905 --> 00:45:10,317
remained to the north
on the mainland

858
00:45:10,341 --> 00:45:14,121
with just a small number
of soldiers guarding it.

859
00:45:14,145 --> 00:45:15,189
Three years later,

860
00:45:15,213 --> 00:45:18,192
a Frenchman by the name
of Dominique de Gourgue

861
00:45:18,216 --> 00:45:23,263
brought his own band of men back
to Florida to exact revenge.

862
00:45:23,287 --> 00:45:28,669
- He claims, "I arrived in
Fort Caroline, what is our fort,

863
00:45:28,693 --> 00:45:31,271
that the Spanish had renamed
Fort San Mateo,

864
00:45:31,295 --> 00:45:35,742
and I surprised them,
and I killed all 200 soldiers,

865
00:45:35,766 --> 00:45:37,277
hanged them at the fort,

866
00:45:37,301 --> 00:45:38,879
and burned the fort
to the ground

867
00:45:38,903 --> 00:45:41,148
and stole all of their
artillery,

868
00:45:41,172 --> 00:45:44,151
and vengeance is ours."

869
00:45:44,175 --> 00:45:48,155
- De Gourgue claimed to have
used a searing iron

870
00:45:48,179 --> 00:45:51,758
to burn a message for the
Spanish in to one of the tables.

871
00:45:51,782 --> 00:45:55,195
- He said, "I do not do this
as unto Spaniards,

872
00:45:55,219 --> 00:45:59,032
but as unto traitors
and robbers and murderers."

873
00:45:59,056 --> 00:46:02,169
But, of course, there is
no burned table at the fort.

874
00:46:02,193 --> 00:46:04,438
In fact, there are not
200 soldiers at the fort.

875
00:46:04,462 --> 00:46:07,674
There were 100 soldiers
stationed at the fort

876
00:46:07,698 --> 00:46:08,942
when he arrived,

877
00:46:08,966 --> 00:46:12,045
and when they heard
the cannon fire

878
00:46:12,069 --> 00:46:15,315
from the mouth of
the Saint John's river,

879
00:46:15,339 --> 00:46:19,820
every single one of those
soldiers packed their supplies

880
00:46:19,844 --> 00:46:21,788
and they left,

881
00:46:21,812 --> 00:46:24,057
and they all made it
to Saint Augustine.

882
00:46:24,081 --> 00:46:26,312
- The fort was never rebuilt.

883
00:46:28,953 --> 00:46:32,199
Very little is known about life
in Saint Augustine

884
00:46:32,223 --> 00:46:36,203
during the years the settlers
lived on Anastasia Island.

885
00:46:36,227 --> 00:46:39,206
No one has ever found
remains of the settlement

886
00:46:39,230 --> 00:46:42,075
which may be buried
underwater now.

887
00:46:42,099 --> 00:46:47,214
Around 1572, they returned
to the other side of the river

888
00:46:47,238 --> 00:46:49,883
and took up residence where
the city of Saint Augustine's

889
00:46:49,907 --> 00:46:51,351
historical district

890
00:46:51,375 --> 00:46:54,488
is located today.

891
00:46:54,512 --> 00:46:57,824
As for Pedro Menéndez, he had
been traveling up and down

892
00:46:57,848 --> 00:47:00,360
the East Coast
during most of this time

893
00:47:00,384 --> 00:47:03,730
establishing a second colony
in South Carolina

894
00:47:03,754 --> 00:47:06,233
and 13 more forts,

895
00:47:06,257 --> 00:47:10,003
but by 1574,
only the two settlements,

896
00:47:10,027 --> 00:47:14,908
Santa Elena
and Saint Augustine remained.

897
00:47:14,932 --> 00:47:19,379
In all that time,
Menéndez never found his son.

898
00:47:19,403 --> 00:47:21,915
He returned to Spain and was
preparing to command

899
00:47:21,939 --> 00:47:23,984
another fleet for the king,

900
00:47:24,008 --> 00:47:26,520
but exactly
nine years to the day

901
00:47:26,544 --> 00:47:28,121
after he marched his troops

902
00:47:28,145 --> 00:47:31,458
through a deadly storm
and captured Fort Caroline,

903
00:47:31,482 --> 00:47:36,129
Pedro Menéndez died at home
in Spain of typhus.

904
00:47:36,153 --> 00:47:38,532
He was 55.

905
00:47:38,556 --> 00:47:40,867
- At the end, he's a romantic.

906
00:47:40,891 --> 00:47:43,403
He's not a person who's looking
for the jewels or the...

907
00:47:43,427 --> 00:47:46,440
He doesn't care about that.

908
00:47:46,464 --> 00:47:48,008
When he died he was ruined.

909
00:47:48,032 --> 00:47:49,276
No money.
No money.

910
00:47:49,300 --> 00:47:51,912
He spent all his money
on his adventures.

911
00:47:51,936 --> 00:47:54,915
He's not a materialist.

912
00:47:54,939 --> 00:47:56,283
He's an...

913
00:47:59,977 --> 00:48:01,321
He's an idealist.

914
00:48:01,345 --> 00:48:05,492
He catches my heart.

915
00:48:05,516 --> 00:48:08,161
- Over the next decade,
Saint Augustine

916
00:48:08,185 --> 00:48:10,430
began to transform
in to the city

917
00:48:10,454 --> 00:48:12,933
that Menéndez had envisioned.

918
00:48:12,957 --> 00:48:15,469
Residents built a town
square patterned

919
00:48:15,493 --> 00:48:18,972
after the plazas in Spain.

920
00:48:18,996 --> 00:48:24,311
- The Plaza, I call it the heart
and soul of Saint Augustine.

921
00:48:24,335 --> 00:48:26,847
Just about everything important
would take place there.

922
00:48:26,871 --> 00:48:29,983
The religious festivals
would take place in the plaza.

923
00:48:30,007 --> 00:48:33,587
Any military parades
or gatherings

924
00:48:33,611 --> 00:48:35,455
would take place in the plaza.

925
00:48:35,479 --> 00:48:38,925
- The plaza also housed
the marketplace.

926
00:48:38,949 --> 00:48:40,327
- And because the market
was there,

927
00:48:40,351 --> 00:48:44,498
we have the first known
regulation of weights

928
00:48:44,522 --> 00:48:46,133
and measures,
so I kind of think of it

929
00:48:46,157 --> 00:48:49,924
as the first consumer
protection laws in the nation.

930
00:48:53,097 --> 00:48:57,344
- We found street deposits
that date back to the late 1500s

931
00:48:57,368 --> 00:48:59,346
or early 1600s.

932
00:48:59,370 --> 00:49:03,417
- Carl Halbirt has overseen Saint
Augustine's archeology program

933
00:49:03,441 --> 00:49:05,385
for more than 25 years.

934
00:49:05,409 --> 00:49:07,621
It's one of the few cities
in the country

935
00:49:07,645 --> 00:49:11,224
that requires an archaeological
dig be conducted

936
00:49:11,248 --> 00:49:14,494
before any new
construction can begin.

937
00:49:14,518 --> 00:49:18,498
- Aviles Street is the
oldest documented

938
00:49:18,522 --> 00:49:21,401
European street
in the United States,

939
00:49:21,425 --> 00:49:26,106
and Philadelphia said,
"Oh, we have the oldest street."

940
00:49:26,130 --> 00:49:28,241
I said, "Philly can
eat my dust."

941
00:49:28,265 --> 00:49:30,911
Clearly we beat them
by 100 years.

942
00:49:30,935 --> 00:49:33,380
- Across from the plaza
on Aviles Street

943
00:49:33,404 --> 00:49:35,649
stood the centerpiece
of it all...

944
00:49:35,673 --> 00:49:39,386
The first parish church
in the United States.

945
00:49:39,410 --> 00:49:43,523
- It was the first building
that one saw

946
00:49:43,547 --> 00:49:47,994
as one entered the inlet
in to the harbor.

947
00:49:48,018 --> 00:49:49,162
- Picture yourself.
You're on a ship.

948
00:49:49,186 --> 00:49:52,999
It takes a month, two months,
to come across the ocean,

949
00:49:53,023 --> 00:49:54,468
terrible, deplorable conditions,

950
00:49:54,492 --> 00:49:58,405
food, sanitation,
fright from storms, pirates,

951
00:49:58,429 --> 00:50:02,409
and you come to Saint Augustine,
and what do they see?

952
00:50:02,433 --> 00:50:05,078
- They would see the church
and the cross

953
00:50:05,102 --> 00:50:09,950
and know that their Christian
home was just ahead of them.

954
00:50:09,974 --> 00:50:15,288
Religion really was an integral
part of their very being,

955
00:50:15,312 --> 00:50:19,025
and you can't exaggerate the
place it took in their lives.

956
00:50:19,049 --> 00:50:22,429
- The church also played a role
in the blending of cultures.

957
00:50:22,453 --> 00:50:26,566
Spanish soldiers began
to marry native women.

958
00:50:26,590 --> 00:50:29,035
- The main thing that had
to happen first

959
00:50:29,059 --> 00:50:31,037
was that you be a Catholic.

960
00:50:31,061 --> 00:50:33,039
Either you convert or you
already were a Catholic,

961
00:50:33,063 --> 00:50:37,711
and so these men, you know,
married women who converted,

962
00:50:37,735 --> 00:50:39,479
who became Catholics.

963
00:50:39,503 --> 00:50:42,382
- 20 to 25 percent
of the marriages

964
00:50:42,406 --> 00:50:46,319
recorded were between a Spaniard
and a Native American.

965
00:50:46,343 --> 00:50:49,990
- There was a lot of
intermarriage because they felt

966
00:50:50,014 --> 00:50:51,458
that these people
were human beings

967
00:50:51,482 --> 00:50:53,059
just like them.

968
00:50:53,083 --> 00:50:55,061
There was such a huge difference

969
00:50:55,085 --> 00:51:00,534
in the acceptance of that
in the Spanish colonies

970
00:51:00,558 --> 00:51:03,169
rather than in
the British colonies.

971
00:51:03,193 --> 00:51:06,473
- In fact, the artifacts
discovered throughout the city

972
00:51:06,497 --> 00:51:10,677
reveal some startling truths
about this country's roots...

973
00:51:10,701 --> 00:51:13,346
That the population
in America's first colony

974
00:51:13,370 --> 00:51:17,150
was a mix of races and cultures
more closely reassembling

975
00:51:17,174 --> 00:51:20,353
the diversity of
America's population today,

976
00:51:20,377 --> 00:51:25,025
not the Anglo version that's
been depicted in textbooks.

977
00:51:25,049 --> 00:51:27,761
- Why did Spanish America emerge

978
00:51:27,785 --> 00:51:30,363
with such a different
kind of society

979
00:51:30,387 --> 00:51:32,532
than English America?

980
00:51:32,556 --> 00:51:35,001
I believe that it has
a great deal to do

981
00:51:35,025 --> 00:51:38,505
with the integration of other
people in to Spanish society

982
00:51:38,529 --> 00:51:40,707
and the exclusion
of other people

983
00:51:40,731 --> 00:51:43,777
from Anglo-American society.

984
00:51:43,801 --> 00:51:47,380
If you really looked at the way
people lived

985
00:51:47,404 --> 00:51:50,650
in colonial English America,

986
00:51:50,674 --> 00:51:53,587
you would only see
English things,

987
00:51:53,611 --> 00:51:57,257
English traditions and
English objects and food.

988
00:51:57,281 --> 00:52:02,429
Most of us look to that
as our history, our origins.

989
00:52:02,453 --> 00:52:05,265
In the Spanish world,
it looked very different.

990
00:52:05,289 --> 00:52:08,268
It was very multicultural
and very integrated.

991
00:52:08,292 --> 00:52:10,670
- You had people
from the Canary Islands.

992
00:52:10,694 --> 00:52:12,472
You had Africans.

993
00:52:12,496 --> 00:52:15,208
You had some converted Jews.

994
00:52:15,232 --> 00:52:19,713
You had a few Italians,
Germans, Irish priests.

995
00:52:19,737 --> 00:52:22,549
- And it really was America's
first melting pot.

996
00:52:22,573 --> 00:52:24,417
- So it's very strange, really,

997
00:52:24,441 --> 00:52:27,900
that that whole part
of the history was eliminated.

998
00:52:30,314 --> 00:52:33,693
- I think that the
United States is richer.

999
00:52:33,717 --> 00:52:35,161
Its history is richer

1000
00:52:35,185 --> 00:52:39,165
because of the existence
of Saint Augustine,

1001
00:52:39,189 --> 00:52:41,167
of the establishment of it.

1002
00:52:41,191 --> 00:52:46,640
It demonstrated that African
and European people

1003
00:52:46,664 --> 00:52:48,708
could live together,

1004
00:52:48,732 --> 00:52:52,712
could benefit from
each other's skills.

1005
00:52:52,736 --> 00:52:57,217
That as a beginning
for the United States,

1006
00:52:57,241 --> 00:52:59,586
if we took that as a beginning,

1007
00:52:59,610 --> 00:53:02,656
I think we would have
a very different picture

1008
00:53:02,680 --> 00:53:05,191
of the United States.

1009
00:53:05,215 --> 00:53:08,194
- Two decades after
Saint Augustine was founded,

1010
00:53:08,218 --> 00:53:11,598
it had become a thriving
16th century town

1011
00:53:11,622 --> 00:53:15,201
complete with shops,
inns and taverns,

1012
00:53:15,225 --> 00:53:19,873
but all of this was
about to be destroyed.

1013
00:53:19,897 --> 00:53:23,476
Suddenly, one day in June 1586,

1014
00:53:23,500 --> 00:53:26,479
a foreboding sight
appeared on the horizon.

1015
00:53:26,503 --> 00:53:28,481
- People looked out
over the inlet

1016
00:53:28,505 --> 00:53:33,820
and saw 23 heavily
armed warships.

1017
00:53:33,844 --> 00:53:38,758
19 auxiliary vessels
which contained 2,000 armed men.

1018
00:53:38,782 --> 00:53:42,228
- This was the fleet of the
notorious English pirate,

1019
00:53:42,252 --> 00:53:46,766
Sir Francis Drake, known
the Spanish as a vicious foe.

1020
00:53:46,790 --> 00:53:50,637
- He had come to attack,
seize, destroy,

1021
00:53:50,661 --> 00:53:55,241
pillage the Spanish city
of Saint Augustine.

1022
00:53:55,265 --> 00:53:58,378
- To the Spanish,
Drake was known as a monster.

1023
00:53:58,402 --> 00:53:59,346
- You Spanish bastards!

1024
00:53:59,370 --> 00:54:03,616
- As a merciless man,
as a power-hungry man,

1025
00:54:03,640 --> 00:54:05,452
as an avaricious man,

1026
00:54:05,476 --> 00:54:08,521
as an inhuman individual,
really.

1027
00:54:08,545 --> 00:54:12,459
- The word Drake was... to the
Spanish, he was a terrorist.

1028
00:54:12,483 --> 00:54:14,194
He was an international
terrorist.

1029
00:54:14,218 --> 00:54:20,266
- The citizens of Saint Augustine
were out-manned and out-gunned.

1030
00:54:20,290 --> 00:54:21,668
- You're the enemy.

1031
00:54:21,692 --> 00:54:25,271
- How could they
possibly survive?

1032
00:54:25,295 --> 00:54:27,273
- You're either with us
or against us.

1033
00:54:27,297 --> 00:54:29,876
If you're against us,
you're going to die.

1034
00:54:29,900 --> 00:54:37,900
♪♪

